revision.text:
'''Acrylic rubber''', known by the chemical name '''alkyl acrylate copolymer''' ('''ACM''') or the tradename '''HyTemp''', is a type of [[rubber]] that has outstanding resistance to hot [[oil]] and [[oxidation]]. It belongs to [[specialty rubber]]s. It has a continuous working temperature of {{convert|150|C|F|abbr=on}} and an intermittent limit of {{convert|180|C|F|abbr=on}}. ACM is polar and doesn't contain unsaturation. It is resistant to [[ozone]] and has low permeability to gases.<ref name="Kothandaraman2008">{{cite book|author=Kothandaraman|title=Rubber Materials|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f5nLU7STtR8C&pg=PA68|accessdate=8 July 2012|date=1 January 2008|publisher=Ane Books India|isbn=978-81-8052-224-6|page=68}}</ref> Its disadvantage is its low resistance to moisture, [[acid]]s, and [[base (chemistry)|base]]s. It should not be used in temperatures below {{convert|-10|C|F|abbr=on}}.
It is commonly used in [[automotive]] [[transmission (mechanics)|transmission]]s and hoses.<ref>{{Citation | title = Rubber selection - A guide to outline properties | url = http://www.merl-ltd.co.uk/2003_materials/rubber12.shtml#acm | accessdate = 2008-12-25}}.</ref> It is also used in shaft seals, adhesives, beltings, gaskets and [[O-rings]].<ref name="Whelan1994">{{cite book|author=Tony Whelan|title=Polymer Technology Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7Qq_vknrP4kC&pg=PA13|accessdate=8 July 2012|year=1994|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-0-412-58180-9|page=13}}</ref><ref name="Gent2001">{{cite book|author=Alan N. Gent|title=Engineering With Rubber: How to Design Rubber Components|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q034u2kLAagC&pg=PA18|accessdate=8 July 2012|year=2001|publisher=Hanser Verlag|isbn=978-1-56990-299-8|pages=18}}</ref> It is used in vibration damping mounts due to the damping properties.<ref name="Kothandaraman2008"/>
==References== {{reflist}}
