{{short description|Ancient Greek mythological figure}}
{{Other uses|Admete (mythology)}}
In [[Greek mythology]], '''Admete''' ({{IPAc-en|æ|d|ˈ|m|iː|t|iː}}; {{lang-grc|Ἀδμήτη}} "the unbroken" or "unwedded, untamed") or '''Admeta''', was one of the [[Oceanid]]s, daughters of [[Oceanus]] and [[Tethys (mythology)|Tethys]].<ref>[[Hesiod]], ''[[Theogony]]'' 349.</ref> Along with her other sisters, she was one of the companions of [[Persephone]] in [[Sicily]] when the god [[Hades]] abducted the daughter of [[Demeter]].<ref>''[[Homeric Hymns|Homeric Hymn]] to [[Demeter]], [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0138%3Ahymn%3D2%3Acard%3D398 421]''</ref> [[Hyginus]] in the preface to his fables calls her Admeto.<ref>[[Gaius Julius Hyginus|Hyginus]]. ''Fabulae, Preface''</ref>

