The '''Anglo-American Petroleum Agreement''' or '''Washington Agreement''' (August 8, 1944) was a failed attempt by the [[British government|British]] and [[American government]]s to establish a lasting agreement to manage international [[petroleum]] supply and demand. The agreement would have established the International Petroleum Commission for the purposes of balancing discordant [[supply and demand]], managing [[Excess supply|surplus]], and bringing order and stability to a [[Market (economics)|market]] laden with oversupply, similar to the [[Railroad Commission of Texas|Texas Railroad Commission]] in the United States. After being concluded, the agreement faced near total opposition from the [[petroleum industry]], prompting [[U.S. President]] [[Franklin Roosevelt]] to withdraw the treaty from ratification consideration and abandon the agreement.<ref>Yergin, Daniel. The Prize. New York: Free P, 2008</ref>
